How to finance the green transition
New York - This week, world leaders gathered at the United Nations in New York to assess the global war with climate change and submit new emissions reduction commitments.
The climate crisis is urgent, and our pace of action is far from enough.
We are unable to enter a state of rapid action.
Accelerating the pace of change requires cooperation and efforts from both the public and private sectors.
Luckily, thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector cooperation to mitigate climate change is increasing.
Under the leadership of UN Climate Envoy Michael Bloomberg, CFLI was established, with the goal of mobilizing private capital at the global level to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report, "Financing the Low Carbon Future," which outlines how to expand green finance to support a orderly low-carbon economic transition and highlights opportunities for public-private cooperation to achieve the 2015 Paris Agreement goals.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the world's largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects.
But now, in response to the call from European leaders and newly elected European Commission President von der Leyen, we are ready to unleash greater ambition and strengthen the EIB's role as the EU's specialized climate bank.
The EIB will mainstream climate consideration, target low-carbon investments, and commit at least €1 trillion over the next decade to low-carbon projects.
To achieve this goal, by 2025, at least 50% of EIB financing will be dedicated to climate action and environmental sustainability.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As a European bank, our task is to invest in Europe's future, and there is no more important issue than climate change.
The more urgent the climate crisis is, the stronger our resolve will be.
Just this summer, European countries have experienced record-breaking heatwaves and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost cities tens of billions of dollars every year, and put even more lives at risk.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as funding new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Changing our investment patterns will accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, nearly half of US coal-fired power plants retired, while the clean energy sector created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 in the coal industry.
Additionally, an increasing number of US cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon plan, launched by the Bloomberg Philanthropies last year, which aims to support the complete decarbonization of the US economy.
As a global community, we must not only invest in clean energy, but also reduce our investment in dirty energy.
Currently, when we look at fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially paying to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investments towards electric vehicles and other transformative technologies that can drive the green transition.
These investments will generate huge returns, including the massive cost savings to public health from reduced air pollution.
Except for this, we can take numerous measures to direct the necessary funds.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, companies and investors have been unaware of climate-related risks, unaware of the reasonableness of reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
This is starting to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in a more sustainable way, and enabling investors to reward companies that take climate change seriously.
Next, we must clarify the investment risks related to green finance.
Cities contribute to over 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few developing-world cities have access to credit ratings.
As a result, investments in clean buses, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reducing projects have been affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives like the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by the Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Thirdly, we need to modernize the grid.
Refunds and tax incentives have promoted the expansion of wind power and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar plans to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, and to overcome intermittency issues.
Furthermore, better grid connectivity can enable regions with a surplus of wind and solar power to supply power to regions in short supply.
Governments can play a leading role in both areas, encouraging more private investment in clean power.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has grown to $136 billion.
However, this is just a drop in the ocean compared to the $100 trillion global bond market.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop sustainable finance standards classification so that investors can compare similar projects, just like standard bonds.
More and better information about investment carbon footprints will enable investors to make informed decisions, driving more private investment towards low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
